{
  "article_id": "Hudson1978_52(1)",
  "paragraphs": [
    [
      {
        "text": "THE EXCITEMENT OF DISCOVERY is just as rewarding in ethnography as in archaeology — and particularly so when one is digging through the exhaustive and overwhelming notes of ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "John P. Harrington",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "jha",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The total disorganization of the notes enhances the thrill of discovery, for one never knows what exciting and important piece of information awaits on the next handwritten page.",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "This recently happened to me as I was poring over Harrington's notes in Boxes 4 and 745 on the ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash Indians",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " of ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "southern California",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "re_socal",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". Box 4 dealt with ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " material culture, while Box 745 contained mostly ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " ritual descriptions. It was quite a surprise to find among these notes material which pertained to the ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "\"lone woman\"* of San Nicolas Island",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ".",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The story of ",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "this woman",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " is well known, popularized by the romanticism of a Robinson Crusoe sort of existence (1836?-1853) on ",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "a tiny island",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ],
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " off the ",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "California coast",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ],
        "entity_key": "re_calcoast",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ".",
        "tropes": [
          8
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " The important accounts of her story have been collected and published by Heizer and Elsasser (1961); there is no need to repeat them here. Instead, Harrington's material will be presented, supplemented where necessary with end notes."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " had a bone knife. It was shaped as shown below.1 "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "2 does not know what kind of bone the knife was made of. She used it for her defense,3 and not to cut things with."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The "
      },
      {
        "text": "Indian woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "told "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "4 that she was going to her home and would come back,5 and they waited and she came back. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hilario Valenzuela",
        "entity_key": "hva",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ",6 \"the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Yaqui",
        "entity_key": "natam_yaqui",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "\", got some trinkets from "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "cand",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " which he took with him. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " never knew what "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hilario",
        "entity_key": "hva",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " did with them.7"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " thinks that the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Indian woman of San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was the last one baptized.8"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The "
      },
      {
        "text": "woman of San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " sang this song when they put her dress on her which they had made for her.10"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "ihi'i hiyuhu\nihi'i hiyuhu\nihi'i hiyuhu hachnuwa l^a nal^ na'al^\nIhi'i giyuhu11"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "Although these words are not understood by "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", he has sort of an understanding of what they mean: \"I continue moving, swaying of the dance, I continue.\""
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "Nolverto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "12 was a Fernandina (Fernandeño who lived in "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", working as a shoe and saddle-maker. He was the only one who could converse with the "
      },
      {
        "text": "woman of San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". He conversed with her freely. The "
      },
      {
        "text": "Cruzeño Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Cruzeno",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " tried, but they could not make her understand.13"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " does not understand the words in this "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " song:"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "tikitiki\nyahamimina tikitiki\nyahamimina tikitiki\nyahamimina tikitiki\ntikitiki weleleshkima\nnishuyahamimina\nweleleshkima\nnishuyahamimina\ntikitiki14"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "1. The drawing is taken from Harrington's sketch of the implement; it is not to scale."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "2. This man is "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando Librado Kitsepawit",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", one of Harrington's principal Ventureño Chumash informants. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was born about 1804, probably on "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Cruz Island",
        "entity_key": "i_scruz",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and spent most of his adult life in "
      },
      {
        "text": "Ventura",
        "entity_key": "ci_ven",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". He died in "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " on June 19, 1915, at an age of about 111 years (Blackburn 1975: 18). Much of Fernando's ethnographic data has been corroborated and used in a number of Chumash studies. These include mythology and stories (Blackburn 1975), history and ritual (Hudson, Blackburn, Curletti and Timbrook 1977), and watercraft, with some plank canoe stories about voyages from "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "i_chi",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " (Hudson, Timbrook and Rempe 1977). The "
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " called "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": "Halashat",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", a Ventureño Chumash word perhaps meaning \"victory\" (Applegate 1975: 28)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "3. It is questionable whether the knife was actually intended as a weapon unless "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " had used it to protect herself from attacks by wild dogs on "
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The Dittman account mentions that "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " did have bone needles and knives, but there are no further details about these objects (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 6)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "4. Malquiares' name appears in other Harrington notes on the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". He is described as a Ventureño Chumash man who took part in Chumash rituals. During the brief seven-week period that "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was alive in "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " many people came to see her and her possessions (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 11); "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hilario Valenzuela",
        "entity_key": "hva",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "5. Nidever's account notes that "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " often visited "
      },
      {
        "text": "the town",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " ("
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ") from the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever house",
        "entity_key": "nideverhouse",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 11). \"Going to her home\" must mean back to the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " house. Perhaps she was in town when she met "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hilario",
        "entity_key": "hva",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "6. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hilario Valenzuela",
        "entity_key": "hva",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " is as yet unidentified; he may have been related to "
      },
      {
        "text": "José Valenzuela",
        "entity_key": "jval",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", husband of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Candalaria",
        "entity_key": "cand",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", one of Harrington's Ventureño informants (Craig 1966: 202)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "7. Some of the woman's possessions were retained by "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Nidevers",
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "sni"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and other local families, while other items such as a feather dress were reportedly sent to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Rome",
        "entity_key": "ci_rom",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": "; we have searched for these objects without success."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "8. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " wrote that "
      },
      {
        "text": "Juana Maria",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was baptized in his house just before death (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 36). Geiger (1965: 152) published the data as entry no. 1183, folio 113, of the Register of Burials of the Presidio, recorded by "
      },
      {
        "text": "Father González Rubio",
        "entity_key": "jru",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Mission Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "mi_santabarbaramission",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". Ecclesiastical burial was given to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Juana Maria",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", the "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", on Oct. 19, 1853, and she received baptism conditionally by "
      },
      {
        "text": "Father Sanchez",
        "entity_key": "sanchez",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", since there was no one who could understand her language."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "9. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Harrington",
        "entity_key": "jha",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " recorded this song and the one which follows it in July, 1913; he did not note the informant but it was probably "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando Librado",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". For a key to pronunciation see (1975: 23-24)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "10. It is not specified which dress elicited the song. According to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Dittman",
        "entity_key": "cdi",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", on her first visit to "
      },
      {
        "text": "their boat",
        "entity_key": "sh_nidever",
        "entity_type": "ship"
      },
      {
        "text": "anchored off "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was given a homemade dress, which she put on with pride (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 10, 19). If this song was sung then it must have been overheard by "
      },
      {
        "text": "one of the Indian crewmen",
        "entity_keys": [
          "cook",
          "msh",
          "poli",
          "nsk",
          "hva"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "and later repeated to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "11. The Hardacre account preserved four poorly spelled words in the language of the \""
      },
      {
        "text": "lone woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "\" (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 4-5). These were examined by Kroeber (1907: 153 and note 3) and determined to be Shoshonean, but it could not be stated whether the language was "
      },
      {
        "text": "Luiseño",
        "entity_key": "natam_Luisenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "Gabrielino",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", or different from these. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Kroeber",
        "entity_key": "akroe",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " added that it was unlikely that her language was understood by any other Indians since she was taken to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", which is located in the territory of non-Shoshonean speaking "
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash Indians",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and that there is no evidence that anyone conversant with Luiseño ever interviewed her. The four known words are nache for \"man\", toygwah for \"sky\", tocah for \"hide\", and puoo-chay for \"body.\" Harrington's recorded songs expand this number greatly, though without benefit of linguistic analysis we cannot know at this time if the songs are truly Nicoleño, or whether their meanings can be worked out. The implication from the story is, however, that her language was a Gabrielino dialect similar to Fernandino. Elsewhere among Harrington's extensive notes (in Boxes 2 and 3) are some ethnographic references which pertain to this question, as well as the languages spoken on the other "
      },
      {
        "text": "southern channel islands",
        "entity_key": "i_southernchi",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". I have somewhat edited this material so that it can be presented here in Harrington form. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin Violin's father",
        "entity_key": "mvfather",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was "
      },
      {
        "text": "a Santa Catalina Island Indian",
        "entity_key": "natam_Catalineno",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". He and "
      },
      {
        "text": "his brother",
        "entity_key": "mvuncle",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", both very old, told "
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin",
        "entity_key": "mvio",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "about the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Indians on the islands",
        "entity_keys": [
          "natam_NicolenoTongva",
          "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
          "natam_chumash"
        ],
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin",
        "entity_key": "mvio",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " in turn later passed it on to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". "
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin",
        "entity_key": "mvio",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " told "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " that the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernandinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " ("
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernandeños",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ") "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara Island",
        "entity_key": "i_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": "'Ichunash",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and that the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Gabrielinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " also called it by this name. It means \"a notice\", as for example the blow of a trumpet. [Ichunash in Chumash means \"whistle\" (Hudson, Blackburn, Curletti and Timbrook 1977)]. "
      },
      {
        "text": "The Indians on this island",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " were "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernandinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " ("
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernandeños",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "). "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Clemente Island",
        "entity_key": "i_scl",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", according to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin Violin's father",
        "entity_key": "mvfather",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "uncle",
        "entity_key": "mvuncle",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", was inhabited by a mixture of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Gabrielinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernandinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_Fernandenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The "
      },
      {
        "text": "people of San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "natam_NicolenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "an old man",
        "entity_key": "mvio",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " said ("
      },
      {
        "text": "Martin Violin",
        "entity_key": "mvio",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " or "
      },
      {
        "text": "his relatives",
        "entity_keys": [
          "mvfather",
          "mvuncle"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "?), came originally from "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Catalina Island",
        "entity_key": "i_scatalina",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". "
      },
      {
        "text": "These people",
        "entity_key": "natam_NicolenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " spoke the language of "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Gabrielinos",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "12. The name "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nolverto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " (also spelled "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nolberto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ") appears occasionally in Harrington's Chumash notes. One note states that "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nolverto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " went with "
      },
      {
        "text": "Jose Polo",
        "entity_key": "jpo",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", alias "
      },
      {
        "text": "Poroi",
        "entity_key": "jpo",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "Manuel Chimuyash",
        "entity_key": "mch",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Manuela Lawi",
        "entity_key": "mla",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Monterrey",
        "entity_key": "ci_mo",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " ("
      },
      {
        "text": "California",
        "entity_key": "st_cal",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " ?) where they were educated. Later "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nolverto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " returned to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", prior to 1853."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "13. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Dittman",
        "entity_key": "cdi",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " wrote that, as far as he knew, none of the Indians who arrived from various places could converse with the \""
      },
      {
        "text": "lone woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "\"; "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Hardacre",
        "entity_key": "eha",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " also noted that no one could communicate with her (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 11, 21, 35)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "14. It is not difficult to conceive of how these songs were recorded. "
      },
      {
        "text": "During her stay in ",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", at the ",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Nidever house",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "nideverhouse",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", ",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Juana Maria",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " would frequently sing and dance in the presence of visitors",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " (Heizer and Elsasser 1961: 11, 21). No doubt "
      },
      {
        "text": "Nolverto",
        "entity_key": "nsk",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and perhaps even "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", witnessed such a performance and memorized the song(s)."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "I wish to express my thanks to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Janice Timbrook",
        "entity_key": "jti",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " for reading and commenting on this paper; her remarks have greatly improved the final result."
